Philippine Stocks: Digital Telecom, Globe, Philippine Telephone

-- B y   I a n   C .   S a y s o n
-- 
2011-03-30T04:45:53Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-30/philippine-stocks-digital-telecom-globe-philippine-telephone.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in Philippine trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the noon close in  Manila .  The Philippine Stock Exchange Index jumped 3 percent to
4,023.74, the steepest advance since Dec. 2.  Digital Telecommunications  Philippines  Inc. (DGTL PM), the
smallest of the nation’s three providers of mobile phone
services, tumbled 15 percent to 1.56 pesos, the sharpest loss
since October 2002.  JG Summit Holdings Inc. (JGS)  , parent of
Digital Telecom, advanced 3.5 percent to 25.35 pesos, the
highest level since Nov. 23.  JG Summit and other parties have agreed to sell their 51.55
percent stake in Digital Telecom to  Philippine Long Distance
Telephone Co. (TEL)  , which also said it will make a tender
for the rest of the company at 1.60 pesos a share. Philippine
Long Distance, the nation’s biggest phone company, gained 16
percent to 2,356 pesos, the steepest advance since November
2000.  Globe Telecom Inc. (GLO)  , the Philippines’ second-
largest mobile phone company, increased 13 percent to 842 pesos,
the biggest gain since January 2001, after Credit Suisse Group
AG said the company will be the “key beneficiary” from the
merger of its two rivals.  Philippine Long Distance’s plan to acquire Digital Telecom
will lead to a “significant improvement in the cellular
competitive environment” and “better” industry revenue and
profitability growth from next year, Chate Benchavitvilai and
Colin McCallum, analysts at Credit Suisse, wrote in today’s
report. Globe had been the “key loser” from the competition so
far, they said.  MUSX Corp. (MUSX)  , a developer of integrated circuits,
climbed 7.1 percent to 7.5 centavos, the sharpest advance since
Nov. 30. Chairman Antonio Tiu is looking at possible renewable
energy ventures to expand the company, a stock exchange filing
showed.  Security Bank Corp. (SECB)   advanced 1 percent to 83.25
pesos, the highest close since Feb. 10. The bank will pay 1 peso
a share in regular and special dividends, a stock exchange
filing showed. The bank will also pay a 20 percent stock
dividend, it said.  To contact the reporter on this story:
